The term "伴" (tomo) is phonetically similar to "友" (companion) or "供" (attendant) and signifies service to the {{ill|Ōkimi|ja|大王 (ヤマト王権)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Great King). Meanwhile, "造" (miyatsuko) denotes leadership over a group. Some Tomonomiyatsuko held high-Ranking {{ill|Kabane|ja|カバネ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} titles like Muraji, but in a narrower sense, it referred to those with mid-to-lower Ranks such as '''Zō (造)''' and '''Obito (首, おびと)'''.<ref>Kano, *Nihonshi Daijiten* (日本史大事典)</ref> Additionally, those from lower-Ranking families were sometimes excluded from Tomonomiyatsuko status and categorized under the {{ill|Hyakuhachibu|ja|百八十部|qq=draft|qq=draft}} class.<ref>Hirano, *Kokushi Daijiten* (国史大辞典)</ref>
Each Tomonomiyatsuko clan had specific administrative duties and led '''Be (部民)''' groups, providing '''human labor or material support''' to the Yamato government.
Under the '''Ritsuryō system''', remnants of the Tomonomiyatsuko system persisted in the '''Banbu (伴部)''' class, which oversaw craftsmanship and administrative work for the state. Records suggest that Banbu was still read as "Tomonomiyatsuko" in certain contexts.
